How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time were overwhelmingly selling only trips to the socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very restricted.
Czech tourists thus travelled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (bels in the Black Sea) and Hungary (the Balathon).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when there was also the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within socialist countries.
In case a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to individually travel to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual way was not possible.
Travel agents were also offering tours to the West at the time, but it was necessary to queue overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who were thus unable to travel at all.
Czechoslovakia's currency was not a freely convercible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to raise funds (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
By far the most common time, however, Czechs vacationed in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this custom still survives today.
Travel by the Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in the countries around the world.
The huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to us for the most popular Croatia at the moment, as it was part of what was then Yugoslavia.
