Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized at a public hospital on Tuesday to test him for the muscle loss he has suffered in the lower extremes, his attending physician reported.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-07) suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is already under control by doctors.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told the TV station Canal N that Fujimori would undergo tests in three days at the National Institute of Neo-patteraphy, where they should find out why he is in pain and why he is losing his strength in his lower extremities.
Aguinaga said that, in his view, Fujimori might be pardoned on humanitarian grounds, but the former president himself does not want a pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and these problems were added by other ailles such as severe erosive gastritis, a cohrit cyst, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Special Police Operations Headquarters.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murdering squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his reign.
