Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelosus Sports Centre (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research was to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity and to trace to Mexican children and young people risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the age of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and a family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause disease such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are being made of anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglicerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined and genes are studied (the genes involved in the development of childhood obesity are being used to identify).
Cruz López said that this research reflected the concern of health professionals over the alarming increase in child's weight.
'Health polls conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was an increase in obesity of 77% for boys and 47% for girls. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight', said the IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators was the assumption that the country's population was different from that of other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic make-up, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in the genes responsible for the emergence of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefits of the participants were to receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, to determine whether they exhibit any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-coloured wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-curkrovical conditions.
The information is confidential so far, with doctors handing it in writing to their parents and explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid the disease.
