Overweight is also due to a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fats and proteins, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asphalt from UNAM there will be no potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty of UNAM, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture with better functionality, independently of the climatic conditions and the temperature
If the cobbles were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Metropolitan area of the Valle de México, Rafael Herrera pointed out to UNAM, a chemical faculty scientist at the Faculty of Chem (FQ), who also added that if the design and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even be able to remove them completely.
In his lecture, the Technology Cause of Bource of Bource, he announced as part of the International Year of Chemistry that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture with similar characteristics to the asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájer believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, improving functionality and reducing the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of the oil, is a cluster of hydrocarbon molecules, molecular-weight molecules called asphaltes, and others with low molecular weights called mortons. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoleastic character of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it acts like a liquid, with a high viscosity at 120 degrees and is almost in firm state at 50 degrees, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to be broken, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist at the Chemistry School observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers are the asphalt insert, made up of small stones topped in the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the insert is topped with asphalt.
When passing through cars or when you create pressure, it is so possible to disinhumst the forces in the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be better distributed, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the asphalt insert was the last layer called the cloak, made up of fine stone, i.e. sand also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rims, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and ensure friction of the road.
As part of the cobbles, the cladding will be subjected to heavy loads, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and care must be of the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially the humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to be remembered. Water in particular has a big impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is damp, the water travels inwards and it is difficult to get out, this causes all layers of pavement to be softened and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that the film of the cladding is the first to be damaged during the potholes and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage is not done at one point, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first signs using the appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National Scientists' System, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each single layer of paving must be commensurate with the load of vehicles and it must be guaranteed that this burden will not be exceeded. This is the only way that we can prevent the frequent emergence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt, and the research is at the beginning. For example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
