This is all explained by the broad smiles of Gazprom's leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete shell to be protected from the moor of naval vessels.
It is at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
In its construction, it was necessary to avoid the minefields from the time of World War II.
"Because of safety, nearly a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the arrangements for the protection of the fauna and flora.
The pipes themselves are a long metal snake weighing like the 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted anywhere by the valves or maintenance stations on its entire length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were little lusted to see the Russian state-owned company permanently settling off their coast.
"In the event of a defect, we stop the passage of the gas in less than 1 minute," specifies Jens Müller.
In the event of a leaking, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, after all, the welds were designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is checked from the outside by the ship by an underwater impot with the ship, while the interior of the pipeline is checked by a device circulating inside.
This dheletoupe-shaped device of 1 metre in diameter is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by the gas.
At the finish line after three days of travel at 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of the metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is the 200 bar at the start and the 100 bar at the finish.
To implement this project the forces of five companies joined forces.
Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake, remains the leading position.
